column4: Consider the recurrence: T(n)=T(⌊n/2⌋)+n for n≥1, T(1)=1. Which is CORRECT?

column4: A binary min-heap contains 105 distinct elements. Let k be the array index of the maximum element. How many possible values can k take?
column7: In a min-heap, the maximum must be in the leaves. A heap with 105 nodes has 52 internal nodes and 53 leaves ⇒ 53 possible positions.

column4: Which statements are TRUE?
column5: ["Symbol table is accessed only during lexical analysis.","LR(1) parsing is sufficient for DCFL.","If LR(1) parser for G has no R/R conflict then LALR(1) for G cannot have R/R conflict.","Data-flow analysis is necessary for runtime memory management."]
column6: ["LR(1) parsing is sufficient for DCFL.","If LR(1) parser for G has no R/R conflict then LALR(1) for G cannot have R/R conflict.","Data-flow analysis is necessary for runtime memory management."]
column7: (A) False; symbol table used throughout. (B) True; DCFL ⊆ LR(1). (C) True; LALR(1) merges compatible states, not creating new R/R conflicts. (D) True; e.g., liveness for allocation/GC.

column4: WB = write-back, WT = write-through; both 2-way set-associative with LRU. Which statements are FALSE?
column5: ["Every write hit in WB sends data to main memory.","Eviction from WT will not send data to main memory.","A read miss in WB will never evict a dirty block.","Each block in WB and WT has a dirty bit."]
column6: ["Every write hit in WB sends data to main memory.","A read miss in WB will never evict a dirty block."]
column7: (A) False: WB defers writes. (B) True: WT keeps memory updated so eviction needn't write. (C) False: read miss may evict a dirty block (write-back needed). (D) True only for WB; WT typically doesn't need dirty bit.

column4: Which statements are TRUE?
column5: ["If L1 and L2 are regular then L1∩L2 must be DCFL.","Every subset of an r.e. language is recursive.","If L and L̄ are both r.e. then L is recursive.","Complement of a context-free language must be recursive."]
column6: ["If L1 and L2 are regular then L1∩L2 must be DCFL.","If L and L̄ are both r.e. then L is recursive.","Complement of a context-free language must be recursive."]
column7: (A) True (regular ⊆ DCFL). (B) False. (C) True by decidability via two recognizers. (D) True: CFL complement is CSL ⊆ recursive.

column4: Let L1={ww | w∈{a,b}*}, L2={a^n b^n c^m | m≥0}, L3={a^n b^m c^m | n≥0}. Which are FALSE?

column7: L1 is not CFL but its complement is CFL; L2 and L3 are CFL but L2∩L3 is not CFL. Thus (A) true; (B),(C),(D) false.

column4: Which of the following is/are true for a group G?
column5: ["If the order of G is 2, then G is commutative","If for all x,y∈G, (xy)^2 = x^2 y^2, then G is commutative","If G is commutative then a subgroup of G need not be commutative","If for all x∈G, x^2=1 (1 is identity), then G is commutative"]

column7: (A) groups of order 2 are abelian; (B) (xy)^2=x^2y^2 ⇒ xy=yx; (C) false—subgroups of abelian groups are abelian; (D) x^2=e ∀x ⇒ x=x^{-1} ⇒ ab=(ab)^{-1}=b^{-1}a^{-1}=ba.

column4: Adjacency matrix A of a simple undirected unweighted graph on n vertices. Which hold?
column5: ["Diagonal entries of A^2 are vertex degrees","If sum of all entries of A ≤ 2(n−1), graph must be acyclic","If the graph is connected then none of the entries of (A^0 + A^1 + … + A^{n−1}) can be zero","If each row and column of A has at least one 1, the graph must be connected"]
column6: ["Diagonal entries of A^2 are vertex degrees","If the graph is connected then none of the entries of (A^0 + A^1 + … + A^{n−1}) can be zero"]
column7: (A) True: (A^2)_{ii}=deg(i). (B) False: small cycles with many isolated vertices. (C) True: sums count paths up to length n−1 between all pairs in a connected graph. (D) False: possible to have two disconnected components each with degrees ≥1.

column4: Simple undirected weighted graph G with all distinct edge weights. Which statements about MST are true?
column5: ["For any nontrivial cut S, the minimum-weight edge crossing the cut is in every MST","G can have multiple spanning trees","One or both of the edges with the 3rd- and 4th-smallest weights are in every MST","The edge with the 2nd-smallest weight is always in every MST"]
column6: ["For any nontrivial cut S, the minimum-weight edge crossing the cut is in every MST","One or both of the edges with the 3rd- and 4th-smallest weights are in every MST","The edge with the 2nd-smallest weight is always in every MST"]
column7: Cut property (A) holds. With distinct weights, the MST is unique, and, beyond the lightest edge, suitable small edges must appear unless they create cycles; per provided solution keys, (C) and (D) are marked true.

column4: Which statement is TRUE for all positive functions f(n)?

column7: when f is a polynomial
column8: If f(n)=a_k n^k+… then f(n^2)≈a_k n^{2k}=Θ((a_k n^k)^2)=Θ(f(n)^2). Other options may fail depending on f.

column4: Which statement is FALSE?
column5: ["TLB does associative search on valid entries using VA page number","If VA hits in TLB but cache misses, the word is in main memory","With hashed page tables, two VAs colliding may have different access times","Using inverted page table, memory access time is always same for all VAs"]
column6: Using inverted page table, memory access time is always same for all VAs
column7: (A) True for typical TLBs; (B) True: TLB gives PA; cache miss falls back to memory; (C) True: chain lengths vary; (D) False: search cost can vary.

column4: Deadlocks: which statements are TRUE?
column5: ["With multiple instances per resource, a cycle in wait-for-graph implies deadlock","If every edge in the resource-allocation graph is an assignment edge, system is not deadlocked","Circular wait is a necessary condition for deadlock","If current allocation is unsafe then a deadlock will necessarily occur"]
column6: ["If every edge in the resource-allocation graph is an assignment edge, system is not deadlocked","Circular wait is a necessary condition for deadlock"]
column7: (A) Not necessarily; (B) True: no pending requests; (C) True (necessary, not sufficient); (D) False: unsafe ≠ deadlocked.

column4: Two 4-bit 2’s complement registers R1 and R2 are added (R1+R2). Which pair causes overflow?
column7: Sum of two negative numbers (−4)+(-6)=−10 which is outside 4-bit 2’s-complement range [−8,7] ⇒ overflow. Others remain in range.

column4: Which statement is TRUE in the relational model?
column5: ["A relation with only two attributes is always in BCNF","BCNF decomposition always preserves all FDs","Every relation has at least one non-prime attribute","If all attributes are prime, the relation is in BCNF"]
column6: A relation with only two attributes is always in BCNF
column7: With only two attributes, any nontrivial FD is either A→B or B→A making determinant a key; decomposition FD preservation need not hold; other claims are not always true.

column4: Schedule S: R1(x) R2(x) R3(x) R4(y) W2(y) W1(x) W3(y) R4(y). The correct topological (conflict) order is:

column7: Girls form 60% of qualified while being only 35% of takers ⇒ qualified girls > qualified boys.

column4: If two distinct non-zero variables x and y are such that (x+y) is proportional to (x−y), then the value of x/y is
column5: ["Depends on xy","Depends only on x and not on y","Depends only on y and not on x","is a constant"]
column7: (x+y)=k(x−y) ⇒ x(1+k)=y(−1+k) ⇒ x/y=(k−1)/(k+1), a constant (for fixed k).
